    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <h2 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.3rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 16px;">How Does Bail Work in Creek County, Oklahoma?</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Angel Bail Bonds provides 24/7 bail bond services for anyone arrested in Creek County, Oklahoma. The Creek County Justice Center at 9175 Ridgeview Street in Sapulpa books inmates around the clock and processes approximately 4,500 inmates per year. After bail is set, Angel Bail Bonds can post the bond and most defendants are released within 2 to 4 hours.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">When someone is arrested in Creek County — whether in Sapulpa, Bristow, Drumright, or anywhere within the county — they are transported to the Creek County Justice Center for booking. The booking process includes identification verification, fingerprinting, a health screening, and entry of charges into the system. The facility opened in July 2005 and serves as the primary detention center for all Creek County law enforcement agencies.</p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Creek County uses a preset bond schedule for many routine misdemeanor charges, which means defendants can sometimes post bail without waiting for a court hearing. For felony charges or more serious offenses, a judge must set bail at arraignment. Oklahoma law requires that bail bond premiums are regulated by the state, and Angel Bail Bonds offers flexible payment options to make the process as affordable as possible.</p>

      <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 28px; margin-bottom: 12px;">What Is the Creek County Courthouse Arraignment Schedule?</h3>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Creek County arraignments are held at 9:00 AM at the Creek County Courthouse, 222 East Dewey Street, Suite 201, Sapulpa, OK 74066. Contact the Court Clerk at (918) 227-2525 for specific docket dates. The District Attorney's Office can be reached at (918) 224-3921 at Suite 302 of the same building.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Creek County is part of Oklahoma's 24th Judicial District. The courthouse handles criminal, civil, and family cases for the entire county. If your loved one's bail requires a judge's approval, Angel Bail Bonds can coordinate with the court schedule to post the bond as quickly as possible after arraignment.</p>

      <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 28px; margin-bottom: 12px;">How Do I Visit Someone in Creek County Justice Center?</h3>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Creek County Justice Center visitation hours are Monday through Friday 7:30 AM to 9:00 PM and Saturday through Sunday 7:30 AM to 2:30 PM. Each inmate is allowed two 25-minute visits per week. Video visitation is available on weekends from 8:00 AM to 3:00 PM by appointment. Call (918) 227-6371 for scheduling.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Visitors should call ahead to confirm availability, as visitation hours may vary by housing unit and security classification. The Creek County Justice Center also offers onsite video visitation on Saturday and Sunday, with appointments that must be made at least 24 hours in advance. The Sapulpa Municipal Jail is a separate facility and can be reached at (918) 224-3862.</p>

      <h3 style="color: var(--navy); font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-top: 28px; margin-bottom: 12px;">What Are Common Bail Amounts in Creek County?</h3>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-700); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Creek County bail amounts vary by charge severity and the judge's discretion. Misdemeanor bonds typically range from $500 to $5,000, while felony bonds can range from $5,000 to $100,000 or more depending on the offense. Judges consider flight risk, community ties, criminal history, and charge severity when setting bail.</strong></p>
      <p style="color: var(--slate-600); font-size: 0.92rem; line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 14px;">Angel Bail Bonds handles all bond amounts in Creek County. Whether the charge is a misdemeanor DUI, a drug offense, a domestic violence charge, or a serious felony, we can post the bond and begin the release process. Call (405) 614-3000 for a free quote on any Creek County bond — we answer 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, including holidays.</p>
    </div>
